It comes a day after 15 crew members of the doomed Sewol ferry, which sank off the southwest coast of South Korea on April 16, went on trial in Gwangju.

Captain Lee Joon-seok, 68, and three senior crew members have been charged with homicide - a charge that could carry the death penalty.

Two others have been charged with fleeing and abandoning ship, with a maximum sentence of life in prison, while nine are accused of negligence, which can also carry jail terms.

Yoo, who has been the focus of a large hunt by police and prosecutors for weeks, is also believed to have contributed to the ferry sinking on April 16 through his alleged corruption.

