Around 200 church members rallied against the raid, with some holding up a large banner, reading: 'We'll protect Yoo Byung-eun even if 100,000 church members are all arrested.'

Yoo, head of the now-defunct predecessor of the ferry's current operator, Chonghaejin, allegedly still controls the company through a complex web of holding companies.

His children and close associates are reportedly large shareholders - and the government has offered a $100,000 (£60,000) bounty for Yoo's eldest son.

The Sewol ferry sinking, one of South Korea's deadliest disasters in decades, happened during a routine journey from Incheon on the mainland to the 
southern holiday island of Jeju.

